Why do we need a new verification model?
In my mind, the current way 256 bit keys and RSA works is trust-dependent architecture with a single point of failure at the key holder
Current criticism and issues with RSA:
RSA is implemented to trust that key holders are in a chain of trust.
Static verification model. It’s a signature that is checked only once at connection time, never during the run process.
No hardware binding. When you steal an RSA key it can be used on any system, anywhere.
Key management: An admin has to oversee rotation of keys, expiry date etc.

What my model does:

 ● Eliminating trust chain (no CAs required) 
 ● Continuous verification (εk > 0 check runs constantly)
 ● Hardware binding (Layer 3 ties verification to physical system)
 ● Self-maintaining (mathematical invariant requires no rotation)"



This is a new example of a computer security verification system.
What I have implemented is a recursive multi layer loop with a third check.
